Recent inflation data and fed chatter suggest 75 bps

The larger-than-expected jump in consumer price growth all but guaranteed the Fed will yet again opt for an aggressive interest rate increase at its next policy meeting in early November and deliver a fourth-consecutive 0.75 percentage point rate rise, the odds of which have been fully priced into the market. - FT, Oct 20, https://www.ft.com/content/963bc01e-c81a-462c-ac2b-ef838cb8bc39

After a 75bps raise in November, which is now considered a done deal, investors think the odds of a 75-basis-point rate hike at the December Fed meeting have nearly doubled after the September inflation report: https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/inflation-september-fed-rate-hike-odds-75-basis-points-december-2022-10

After yesterday's inflation data for September came in (again) way hotter than expected, a 75bps hike in November seems like a done deal, which would put the question safely and squarely into bin 5: https://www.cmegroup.com/trading/interest-rates/countdown-to-fomc.html

The Fed is expected to deliver a fourth straight 75-basis-point rate hike when it meets early next month - Reuters, Oct 5, https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/fed-determined-fix-problematic-inflation-daly-says-2022-10-05/
at 3.25 currently and two meetings left and expectations for more hikes, very unlikely to not get above 3.75

We are currently at 1%. They have already slowed from one 50 basis point increase to a 25 increase in May. The expectation is that inflation will start to trend downward as spending decreases and output increases. However unemployment has remained low and home values have stayed relatively high which gives the Fed some extra room to continue to increase rates without significant downside. The high oil prices however make a recession a very likely and hard to balance risk that I think will keep the Fed raising rates incrementally in the 25 basis point range unless the current trends reverse. Unless they regularly continue with 50 basis point jumps then they will not exceed 3.25 and likely will stay below 2.25
